# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: digitalocean
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:digitalocean/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A **data center** is a facility used to house computer systems and associated components, such as telecommunications and storage systems.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Data centers are critical infrastructure for the storage and processing of information, and they support the global financial system, cloud services, machine learning, and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Data centers vary widely in terms of size, power and water requirements, and overall structure.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Hyperscale and colocation facilities collectively account for approximately 74% of U.S. server energy consumption as of 2023, a share that has grown significantly over the past decade as workloads have migrated away from enterprise on-premises infrastructure.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Since IT operations are crucial for business continuity, a data center generally includes redundant or backup components.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Other important design considerations are power supply, network infrastructure, environmental controls (e.g., cooling, fire suppression), and various measures for physical and data security.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Large data centers operate at an industrial scale, requiring significant energy.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Estimated global data center electricity consumption in 2024 was around 415 terawatt hours (TWh), or about 1.5% of global electricity demand.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The International Energy Agency (IEA) projects that data center electricity consumption could double by 2030.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of data center infrastructure has prompted regulatory debates in multiple jurisdictions regarding tax incentives, electricity grid impacts, water consumption, and compatibility with state and national climate commitments.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Rapid growth of the AI industry is leading to strain on electric grids and increased electricity costs for consumers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] This in turn has drawn growing opposition to new data centers from local people who would bear the burdens of social and environmental impacts, such as energy and water use, while faraway actors and institutions would receive the projects' benefits.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] These opposition movements have materialized especially in parts of Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Billions of dollars in projects were halted or delayed by data center resistances in the U.S. between May 2024 and June 2025.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Data centers are usually classified according to their ownership model, scale, and intended use.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] However, these classifications are not mutually exclusive from each other, and they may overlap depending on the operational structure and service model of the particular data center.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Enterprise data centers are owned and operated by a single organization for their own internal information technology (IT) needs, rather than for commercial hosting of other companies' data.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] They used to be essential infrastructures; as in 2014, enterprise data centers accounted for over 60% of the U.S. server energy consumption, but this share fell sharply to about 10% by 2023 as workloads migrated to hyperscale and colocation facilities.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Energy efficiency at an enterprise data center tends to be significantly lower than at hyperscale facilities due to its cooling, which can account for over 30% of electricity consumption at enterprise sites, compared to roughly 7% at efficient hyperscale data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The shift away from enterprise facilities toward cloud and colocation infrastructure is one of the defining structural trends of the previous decade.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Colocation centers provide shared physical infrastructure, such as power, cooling, space, etc., to multiple tenants who lease space rather than building their own facilities.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Colocation data centers reduce expenditure for organizations while enabling operators to achieve economies of scale in power procurement and cooling efficiency.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Some of the largest data centers in the world are colocation centers, and this category accounted for about 22% of worldwide data center capacity as of 2024, making them the second-largest category by capacity after hyperscale facilities.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Major colocation providers include Equinix, Switch, COPT, and Digital Realty, which operate facilities across multiple continents.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Hyperscale data centers are large-scale facilities, typically exceeding 100 megawatts of power capacity, designed to support massive, scalable computing workloads for cloud services, AI training, and large-scale data processing.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] By the end of 2024, there were 1,136 operational hyperscale data centers globally, a figure that doubled over the previous five years, with the U.S. accounting for approximately 54% of total hyperscale capacity.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In particular, the three largest operators, Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud, collectively account for approximately 59% of all hyperscale data center capacity globally.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] As a growing trend, hyperscale data centers represented about 41% of worldwide data center capacity in 2024 and are projected to exceed 60% by 2029 as enterprise on-premises infrastructure continues to decline.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Moreover, as artificial intelligence (AI) is becoming widely used, AI data centers are being built more rapidly, and they can consume as much electricity as 100,000 households, more than conventional data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Since 2024, there has been widespread grassroots Opposition to AI Data Centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Edge data centers are smaller facilities, typically ranging from 1 to 10 megawatts.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] They are positioned closer to end users or data sources to reduce network latency and support real-time applications, such as autonomous vehicles, industrial automation, and content delivery.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Unlike hyperscale data centers, edge data centers are intentionally distributed across many locations rather than consolidated, with deployments occurring in urban areas, cell tower sites, as well as industrial locations.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The growth of edge computing infrastructure has been tied to the expansion of 5G wireless networks and the increasing use of Internet of Things (IoT) devices, which generate data that is more efficiently processed near its source than transmitted to a centralized data center.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Micro data centers (MDCs) are access-level data centers that are smaller in size than traditional data centers but provide the same features.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] They are typically located near the data source to reduce communication delays, as their small size allows several MDCs to be spread out over a wide area.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] MDCs are suited to user-facing, front end applications.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] They are commonly used in edge computing and other areas where low latency data processing is needed.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Modularity and flexibility are key elements in allowing a data center to grow and change over time.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Data center modules are pre-engineered, standardized building blocks that can be configured and moved as needed.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A modular data center may consist of data center equipment contained within shipping containers or similar portable containers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Components of the data center can be prefabricated and standardized, which facilitates moving if needed.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] These modular data centers are useful for IT disaster recovery.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Mobile data centers are also used to move large quantities of data, by physically transporting the hardware that contains it, and in cryptocurrency mining, where fleets of mobile data centers are transported to take advantage of cheaper sources of energy.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Data centers have their roots in the huge computer rooms of the 1940s, typified by the Electronic Numerical Integrator and Computer (ENIAC), one of the earliest examples of a data center.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Early computer systems were complex to operate and maintain, and required a special environment in which to operate.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Many cables were necessary to connect all of the components, and methods to accommodate and organize these were devised such as standard racks to mount equipment, raised floors, and cable trays (installed overhead or under the elevated floor).
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A single mainframe required a great deal of power and had to be cooled to avoid overheating.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Security became important – computers were expensive, and were often used for government and military purposes.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] As such, basic design guidelines for controlling access to the computer room were devised.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] During the microcomputer industry boom of the 1980s, computers started to be deployed everywhere, in many cases with little or no care about operating requirements.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] However, as information technology (IT) operations started to grow in complexity, organizations grew aware of the need to control IT resources.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The availability of inexpensive networking equipment, coupled with new standards for the network structured cabling, made it possible to use a hierarchical design that put servers in a specific room inside the company.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The use of the term *data center*, as applied to specially designed computer rooms, started to gain popular recognition about this time.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] During the dot-com bubble (1997–2000), there was a boom in data center construction because companies needed fast Internet connectivity and non-stop operation to establish their Internet presence.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The global data center market saw steady growth in the 2010s, with a notable acceleration in the latter half of the decade.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] According to Gartner, worldwide data center infrastructure spending reached $200 billion in 2021, representing a 6% increase from 2020 despite economic challenges posed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2024, global energy consumption from data centers was 620 TWh, with 80% of that consumption concentrated in the U.S., China, and the United Kingdom.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Colocation centers were the most common category worldwide, with 4,799 colocation centers in 127 countries.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In that year, the largest data center in the world was Citadel, owned by Switch, at the Tahoe Reno Industrial Center in Reno, Nevada, occupying 7.2 million square feet.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Growth of the data center industry has prompted local resistance.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A 2023 survey found social mobilizations against the industry in Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] These movements expressed concern about the centers' energy and water use, pollution, and impact on agriculture or the landscape.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A 2026 poll by *Politico* suggested that resistance to growth of the industry would make candidates' stance on data centers a significant issue for voters in the U.S.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The U.S. hosted 5,381 data centers in March 2024, the highest number of any country worldwide, accounting for 40% of the global market in 2023.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] As of 2023, about 80% of U.S. data center load was concentrated in 15 states, led by Virginia and Texas.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] As of 2025, roughly one third of America's data centers were in three states: Virginia (643), Texas (395), and California (319).
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The largest concentration of data centers in the world is in Northern Virginia, with over 250 facilities in the region.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2025, Georgia was the fastest growing data center hub in the U.S., having enacted several state tax exemptions for the industry and hosting between 100 and 150 centers in the state.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Local governments have responded to the growing industry in Georgia with a variety of local ordinances to guide permitting of these facilities.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The consultancy firm McKinsey & Co., projected U.S. demand to double to 35 gigawatts (GW) by 2030, up from 17 GW in 2022.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A study published by the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) in May 2024 estimated that data centers could consume between 4.6% and 9.1% of the country's electricity generation by 2030.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] GDP growth was only 0.1% without the investments in data centers for artificial intelligence.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Data centers house critical computing resources in a controlled environment and must generally operate with very high availability.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Key design elements include providing power for the equipment, temperature and humidity control, cabling, fire safety, and security.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] For this reason, a data center has to offer a secure environment that minimizes the chances of a security breach.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Industry research company International Data Corporation (IDC) puts the average age of a data center at nine years old.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Gartner, another research company, says data centers older than seven years are obsolete.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The growth in data (163 zettabytes by 2025) is one factor driving the need for data centers to modernize.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Rapid obsolescence of data center equipment was a concern by at least 2007, and in 2011, Uptime Institute was concerned about aging equipment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The topology proposed in this document is intended to be applicable to any size data center.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Telcordia GR-3160, *NEBS Requirements for Telecommunications Data Center Equipment and Spaces*, provides guidelines for data center spaces within telecommunications networks, and environmental requirements for the equipment intended for installation in those spaces.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] These criteria were developed jointly by Telcordia and industry representatives.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] They may be applied to data center spaces housing data processing or IT equipment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Power supplies, either back up or continuous onsite power, consist of one or more uninterruptible power supplies, battery banks, diesel, gas turbine, and/or gas engine generating sets.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Greater primary fuel energy efficiency can be achieved with the use of cogeneration technology, generating electricity, heating, and cooling onsite.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] To prevent single points of failure, all elements of the electrical systems, including backup systems, are typically given redundant copies, and critical servers are connected to both the *A-side* and *B-side* power feeds.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] This arrangement is often made to achieve N+1 redundancy in the systems.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Static transfer switches are sometimes used to ensure instantaneous switchover from one supply to the other in the event of a power failure.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Options for low-voltage cable routing might include data cabling that is routed through overhead cable trays; raised floor cabling, both for security reasons and to avoid the extra cost of cooling systems over the racks; and anti-static tiles for flooring, especially in low-cost data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Maintaining suitable temperature and humidity levels is critical to preventing equipment damage caused by overheating.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Overheating can cause components (usually the silicon or copper of the wires or circuits) to melt, causing loose connections and fire hazards.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Typical temperature control methods include air conditioning and indirect cooling, such as the use of outside air, indirect evaporative cooling units, and seawater cooling.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Airflow management is the practice of achieving data center cooling efficiency by preventing the recirculation of hot exhaust air and by reducing bypass airflow.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Common approaches include hot-aisle/cold-aisle containment and the deployment of in-row cooling units, which position cooling directly between server racks to intercept exhaust heat before it mixes with room air.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Humidity control prevents moisture and related issues.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] For example, excess humidity can cause dust to adhere more readily to fan blades and heat sinks, impeding air cooling and leading to higher temperatures.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Cold aisle containment is done by exposing the rear of equipment racks, while the fronts of the servers are enclosed with doors and covers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] This is similar to how large-scale food companies refrigerate and store products.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Computer cabinets/server farms are often organized for containment of hot/cold aisles.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Proper air duct placement prevents cold and hot air from mixing.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Rows of cabinets are paired to face each other so the cool and hot air intakes and exhausts do not mix air, which would severely reduce cooling efficiency.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Alternatively, a range of underfloor panels can create efficient cold air pathways directed to the raised-floor vented tiles.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Either the cold aisle or the hot aisle can be contained.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Another option is fitting cabinets with vertical exhaust duct chimneys.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Hot exhaust pipes/vents/ducts can direct the air into a plenum space above a dropped ceiling and back to the cooling units or to outside vents.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] With this configuration, traditional hot/cold aisle configuration is not required.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Data centers feature fire protection systems, including passive and active design elements, as well as implementation of fire prevention programs in operations.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Smoke detectors are usually installed to provide early warning of a fire.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Although the main room usually does not allow wet pipe-based systems due to the fragile nature of circuit boards, there are systems that can be used in the rest of the facility or in cold/hot aisle air circulation systems that are closed systems.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] These include sprinkler systems and misting, the latter of which uses high pressure to create extremely small water droplets and can be used in sensitive rooms due to the nature of the droplets.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] However, there are other means to put out fires, especially in Sensitive areas, usually using gaseous fire suppression, of which Halon gas was the most popular, until the negative effects of producing and using it were discovered.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Physical access to data centers is usually restricted.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Layered security often starts with fencing, bollards, and mantraps.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Video camera surveillance and permanent security guards are almost always present if the data center is large or contains sensitive information.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Fingerprint recognition is starting to become commonplace.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Logging access is required by some data protection regulations; some organizations tightly link this to access control systems.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Multiple log entries can occur at the main entrance, entrances to internal rooms, and at equipment cabinets.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Access control at cabinets can be integrated with intelligent power distribution units, so locks are networked through the same appliance.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Data center transformation takes a step-by-step approach through integrated projects carried out over time.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] This differs from a traditional method of data center upgrades, which takes a serial and siloed approach.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Typical projects within a data center transformation initiative include standardization/consolidation, virtualization, automation, and security.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Data center consolidation consists of reducing the number of data centers and avoiding *server sprawl* (both physical and virtual), which often includes replacing aging data center equipment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] This process is aided by standardization, which makes these systems follow a uniform set of configurations to simplify and improve efficiency.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Automating tasks such as provisioning, configuration, patching, release management, and compliance are other ways in which data centers can be upgraded.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] These changes are needed not just when facing fewer skilled IT workers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Lastly, security initiatives integrate the protection of virtual systems with existing security for physical infrastructures.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The first raised floor computer room was made by IBM in 1956 to allow access for wiring.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] During the 1970s, raised floors became more common because they allow cool air to circulate more efficiently.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A raised floor standards guide (GR-2930) was developed by Telcordia Technologies, a subsidiary of Ericsson.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The "lights-out" data center, also known as a darkened or dark data center, is a data center that has largely eliminated the need for direct access by personnel, except under extraordinary circumstances.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Due to the lack of need for staff to enter the data center, it can be operated without lighting.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] All of the devices are accessed and managed by remote systems, with automation programs used to perform unattended operations.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In addition to the energy savings, reduction in staffing costs, and the ability to locate the site further from population centers, implementing a lights-out data center also reduces the threat of malicious attacks upon the infrastructure.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) regulations require monitoring of noise levels inside data centers if noise exceeds 85 decibels.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The average noise level in server areas of a data center may reach as high as 92–96 dB(A).
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Residents living near data centers have described the sound as "a high-pitched whirring noise 24/7", saying "It's like being on a tarmac with an airplane engine running constantly ...
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] External sources of noise include HVAC (heating, ventilation, and air conditioning) equipment and energy generators.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Location factors include proximity to power grids, telecommunications infrastructure, networking services, transportation lines, and emergency services.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Other considerations should include flight paths, neighboring power drains, geological risks, and climate (associated with cooling costs).
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Local political considerations, such as availability of subsidies and lack of opposition, are also important factors in locating data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Various metrics exist to measure the data-availability that results from data-center availability beyond 95% uptime, with the top of the scale counting how many *nines* can be placed after *99%*.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The costs of avoiding downtime should not exceed the cost of the downtime itself.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Dynamic infrastructure provides the ability to intelligently, automatically, and securely move workloads within a data center anytime, anywhere, for migrations, provisioning, to enhance performance, or build co-location facilities.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] It also facilitates performing routine maintenance on either physical or virtual systems, all while minimizing interruption.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A related concept is Composable Infrastructure, which allows for the dynamic reconfiguration of the available resources to suit needs, only when needed.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Communications in modern data centers are most often based on networks running the Internet protocol suite.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Data centers contain a set of routers and switches that transport traffic between the servers and to the outside world, which are connected according to the data center network architecture.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Redundancy of the internet connection is often provided by using two or more upstream service providers (see Multihoming).
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Some of the servers at a data center are used for running the basic internet and intranet services needed by internal users in the organization, e.g., e-mail servers, proxy servers, and DNS servers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Network security elements are also usually deployed: firewalls, VPN gateways, intrusion detection systems, and so on.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Also common are monitoring systems for the network and some of the applications.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Additional off-site monitoring systems are also typical, in case of a failure of communications inside the data center.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Energy consumption and the environmental impacts it creates are a central issue for data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Power draw ranges from a few kilowatts (kW) for small server racks to several tens of megawatts (MW) for large facilities.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Modern hyperscale data centers can exhibit power densities exceeding 100 times those of conventional office buildings, primarily due to the high concentration of servers and cooling systems required to manage continuous digital workloads.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] For higher power density facilities, electricity costs are a dominant operating expense and account for over 10% of the total cost of ownership (TCO) of a data center.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] As of 2024, data centers in the U.S. are primarily powered by natural gas, which supplies 40% of their electricity (with renewable energy at 24%, nuclear at about 20%, and coal at about 15%).
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The *Associated Press* reported that electricity for AI data centers in the U.S. would likely come from natural gas or oil, as companies prefer using currently available power plants, which primarily use fossil fuels.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Fossil energy is also often cheaper in locations where data centers are developed, and experts believe that energy demands from generative AI and data centers would be difficult to fulfill with renewable energy alone.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Some companies such as Google, Amazon, and Meta have expressed interest in nuclear power for their data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] As of 2020, according to the IEA, solar photovoltaic-generated electricity is at its lowest cost in history.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Other data centers, including xAI's Colossus, OpenAI's Stargate, and Meta's Prometheus use their own off-grid natural gas plants.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Electric vehicle and lithium-ion batteries have also been used for powering data centers, including for Colossus.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Power utility companies make upgrades to their infrastructure to handle demands of new data centers, and the price for these changes typically falls on residential or smaller commercial consumers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2025, the Mountain Valley Pipeline announced plans to expand its capacity by 25% to meet energy needs for data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In December 2025, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) published a unanimous order allowing data centers in the U.S. to have a direct connection with power plants.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] United States Secretary of Energy Chris Wright expressed support for un-retiring coal plants to power AI data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Electricity demands from AI data centers have slowed or reversed the retirement of peaking power plants in the U.S.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] For example, in 2025, Southern Company announced that energy use from data centers would prevent the company from retiring coal-fired power plants as it had earlier promised.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In Nevada, the Desert Research Institute (DRI) calculated that 35% of the state's energy production could go to data centers by the year 2030 if all projects planned in the state as of 2026 are completed.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] DRI also stated, in areas where there are clusters of data centers, local consumers may end up paying the extra cost of expanding infrastructure.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2024, data centers were estimated to account for about 1.5% of global electricity consumption (approximately 415 TWh) and around 1% of greenhouse gas emissions according to U.S.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] However, the rapid expansion is causing projections to rise sharply.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Due to accelerated demand from AI, data center's global electricity consumption is projected to more than double to around 945 TWh by 2030 in the IEA's base-case scenario, which represents just under 3% of 2030 total global electricity consumption.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] This growing electricity demand, much of which is still generated by fossil fuels, increases the potential environmental impacts.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In addition to operational energy demand, embodied life cycle emissions should be considered, which include the extraction, manufacturing, transportation, and recycling or disposal of materials used in the construction of facilities and hardware.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Global data center carbon dioxide emissions are projected to rise from an estimated 220 million tonnes in 2024 to 300–320 million tonnes by 2035.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google and Microsoft each consumed more power than over 100 countries.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] As a result, there is increasing industry pressure for decarbonization.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Companies are pursuing direct clean energy agreements, such as Tencent who has pledged to be carbon neutral by 2030, and Microsoft's 2024 agreement to re-open the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant to provide 100% of the electric power for its AI data centers for 20 years.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The most commonly used energy efficiency metric for data centers is power usage effectiveness (PUE), calculated as the ratio of total power entering the data center divided by the power used by IT equipment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] PUE measures the percentage of power used by overhead devices (cooling, lighting, etc.).
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The average U.S. data center has a PUE of 2.0, meaning two watts of total power (overhead + IT equipment) for every watt delivered to IT equipment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] State-of-the-art data centers are estimated to have a PUE of roughly 1.2.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Google publishes quarterly efficiency metrics from its data centers in operation.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] PUEs of as low as 1.01 have been achieved with two-phase immersion cooling.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The EPA has an Energy Star rating for standalone or large data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] To qualify for the ecolabel, a data center must be within the top quartile in energy efficiency of all reported facilities.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The Energy Efficiency Improvement Act of 2015 (U.S.) requires federal facilities—including data centers—to operate more efficiently.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] California's Title 24 (2014) of the California Code of Regulations mandates that every newly constructed data center must have some form of airflow containment in place to optimize energy efficiency.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The European Union (EU) also has a similar initiative: EU Code of Conduct for Data Centres.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Efficiency improvements and renewable energy integration are helping offset some emissions, but fossil fuels remain a major electricity source for data center operations worldwide.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2011, server racks in data centers were designed for more than 25 kW, and the typical server was estimated to waste about 30% of the electricity it consumed.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The energy demand for information storage systems is also rising.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A high-availability data center is estimated to have a 1 MW demand and consume $20 million in electricity over its lifetime, with cooling representing 35% to 45% of the data center's total cost of ownership.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Calculations show that in two years, the cost of powering and cooling a server could be equal to the cost of purchasing the server hardware.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Research in 2018 showed that a substantial amount of energy could still be conserved by optimizing IT refresh rates and increasing server use.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Research for optimizing task scheduling is also underway, with researchers looking to implement energy-efficient scheduling algorithms that could reduce energy consumption by anywhere between 6% and 44%.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2011, Facebook, Rackspace, and others founded the Open Compute Project (OCP) to develop and publish open standards for greener data center computing technologies.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] As part of the project, Facebook published the designs of its server, which it had built for its first dedicated data center in Prineville.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Making servers taller left space for more effective heat sinks and enabled the use of fans that moved more air with less energy.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] By not buying commercial off-the-shelf servers, energy consumption due to unnecessary expansion slots on the motherboard and unneeded components, such as a graphics card, was also saved.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2016, Google joined the project and published the designs of its 48V DC shallow data center rack.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] This design had long been part of Google data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] By eliminating the multiple transformers usually deployed in data centers, Google had achieved a 30% increase in energy efficiency.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2017, sales for data center hardware built to OCP designs topped $1.2 billion and are expected to reach $6 billion by 2021.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Power is the largest recurring cost to the user of a data center.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2008, the ASHRAE recommended a temperature range of 64.4 °F (18.0 °C) to 80.6 °F (27.0 °C), though some data centers could operate at higher temperatures.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] However, cooling at or below 70 °F (21 °C) wastes money and energy.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Furthermore, overcooling equipment in environments with a high relative humidity can expose equipment to a high amount of moisture that facilitates the growth of salt deposits on conductive filaments in the circuitry.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A **power and cooling analysis**, also referred to as a thermal assessment, measures the relative temperatures in specific areas as well as the capacity of the cooling systems to handle specific ambient temperatures.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Power cooling density is a measure of how much square footage the center can cool at maximum capacity.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The cooling of data centers is the second largest power consumer after servers, with cooling taking about 7% to 30% of energy usage (depending on efficiency), compared to an average of 60% of energy used by servers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] An energy efficiency analysis measures the energy use of data center IT and facilities equipment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A typical energy efficiency analysis measures factors such as a data center's Power Use Effectiveness (PUE) against industry standards, identifies mechanical and electrical sources of inefficiency, and identifies air-management metrics.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] However, the limitation of most current metrics and approaches is they do not include IT in the analysis.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Case studies have shown that by addressing energy efficiency holistically in a data center, major efficiencies can be achieved that are not possible otherwise.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Thermal zone mapping uses sensors and computer modeling to create a three-dimensional image of the hot and cool zones in a data center.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] This information can help identify optimal positioning of data center equipment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] For example, critical servers might be placed in a cool zone that is serviced by redundant AC units.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Data centers use a lot of power, consumed via two main usages: the power required to run the equipment and the power required to cool the equipment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Power efficiency reduces the first category.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Cooling cost reduction through natural means includes location decisions.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] When the focus is avoiding good fiber connectivity, power grid connections, and people concentrations to manage the equipment, a data center can be miles away from users.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Mass data centers like Google or Facebook do not need to be near population centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Arctic locations that can use outside air, which provides cooling, are becoming more popular.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Countries with favorable conditions, such as Canada, Finland, Sweden, Norway, and Switzerland are trying to attract cloud computing data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Singapore lifted a three-year ban on new data centers in April 2022.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A major data center hub for the Asia-Pacific region, Singapore lifted its moratorium on new data center projects in 2022, granting four new projects, but rejecting more than 16 data center applications from over 20 received.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] It is very difficult to reuse the heat that comes from air-cooled data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] For this reason, data center infrastructures are more often equipped with heat pumps.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of artificial intelligence (AI) and high-performance computing workloads has increased attention on data center power infrastructure, particularly the relationship between electrical reliability, deployment timelines, energy costs, and decarbonization objectives.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Industry publications have described phased approaches to infrastructure development that enable operators to deploy power capacity rapidly while maintaining pathways toward lower-carbon energy systems as technologies, fuel availability, grid capacity, and economics evolve.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Recent industry discussion has also emphasized "speed-to-power" as a significant consideration in data center development, reflecting the growing importance of securing electrical capacity and resilient power systems within increasingly compressed project timelines.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In the 2020s, the rapid growth of data center construction gave rise to policy debates over tax incentives, electricity grid, water resources, and climate commitments.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] By 2024, at least 36 U.S. states had introduced specific tax incentives aimed at attracting data center investment, most often in the form of sales tax exemptions on servers, networking equipment, and electricity.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Virginia hosts the largest concentration of data centers in the U.S., and a December 2024 audit by its Joint Legislative Audit and Review Commission (JLARC) put the industry's annual contribution at roughly 74,000 jobs and $9.1 billion in gross state product.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The audit reported that the state's sales and use tax exemption was claimed by about 90% of operators and that reduced state revenue by an estimated $928 million in fiscal year 2023.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Thus, JLARC concluded that ending the exemption would likely shrink Virginia's share of new data center investment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Economists have debated the effectiveness of such incentives more broadly.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Further, research by Timothy Bartik of the Upjohn Institute estimated that economic development incentives change firm location decisions in only 2% to 25% of cases.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In response to tax exemption policies, several jurisdictions have started to reevaluate incentives for data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2024, the Georgia General Assembly passed legislation to terminate the state's data center sales tax exemption.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] However, the bill was ultimately vetoed by Governor Brian Kemp.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In another case in 2026, the Virginia Senate voted 28 to 12 to phase out the state's data center sales tax exemption as part of broader budget negotiations.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Most large data centers use water for evaporative cooling of their servers, and the volumes involved have drawn growing scrutiny.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A 2021 study in *npj Clean Water* estimated that U.S. data centers directly consume about 1.7 billion liters of water per day, with up to 57% of that drawn from potable supplies, and noted that fewer than one-third of operators measured their water use at the time.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] A separate study published in *Environmental Research Letters* found that about one-fifth of direct water use by U.S. data centers came from moderately or highly water-stressed watersheds, and that nearly half of the country's servers ran on electricity drawn from water-stressed regions.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] According to a 2024 Berkeley Lab report, data centers in the U.S. had used approximately 17 billion gallons of water.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The same report expected hyperscale data centers specifically to use 16 to 33 billion gallons of water per year by 2028.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In Virginia, the December 2024 JLARC audit reported that data centers in the state consumed about 2.1 billion gallons of water in 2023, an 86% increase since 2019, and that roughly one-third of that came from reclaimed water rather than potable supplies.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The audit recommended that local governments be authorized to require water-use estimates as part of the data center permitting process.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] There is no federal U.S. standard requiring data center operators to disclose water consumption, and access to facility-level data has often been limited by non-disclosure agreements (NDAs) with host municipalities.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2022, the city of The Dalles, Oregon, settled a public records lawsuit brought by *The Oregonian*, after which Google ended its nationwide practice of treating site-level water use as a trade secret.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2025, several states considered legislation to require data centers to disclose water use, including bills in Virginia, California, and New Jersey, although each was vetoed by the state's governor that year.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The growth of data center electricity demand in the 2020s has prompted regulatory debates over grid capacity, transmission planning, and how the costs of new infrastructure should be allocated among customers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The 2024 Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory (LBNL) report on U.S. data center energy use, prepared at the request of the U.S.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Congress, estimated that data centers accounted for about 4.4% of national electricity consumption in 2023 and projected a rise to between 6.7% and 12% by 2028, depending on growth scenarios.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2025, the IEA projected that data centers would account for nearly half of new U.S. electricity demand growth through 2030.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC), the federally designated electric reliability organization for the U.S., identified data centers as the single largest driver of projected demand growth in its 2024 long-term reliability assessment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Additionally, NERC documented a voltage event in the PJM Interconnection region in July 2024, in which roughly 1,500 megawatts of data center load disconnected simultaneously across about 60 facilities.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] How the costs of meeting this demand are shared has also become a central policy question.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The JLARC audit in 2024 estimated that, without any changes to how rates are designed, typical residential customers of Dominion Energy Virginia could see their bills rise by $14 to $37 per month by 2040 because of data center-driven grid investment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] As such, the report recommended creating a separate customer rate class for large data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Some researchers have urged caution in interpreting demand projections.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Furthermore, a 2024 commentary in the journal *Joule* argued that public estimates of future data center electricity use vary widely and that utilities have historically over-forecasted load growth, and called for more transparent data on actual facility-level consumption.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The growth of data centers has raised questions about whether the renewable energy commitments made by their operators are consistent with broader climate goals.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Many large operators report meeting electricity-related emissions targets through annual purchases of renewable energy certificates (RECs) or matching their total annual consumption with renewable generation.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2022, a study by *Nature Climate Change* analyzed 115 companies with Science Based Targets.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] It found that about 42% of their reported Scope 2 emissions reductions disappeared once REC-based claims were excluded.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] This directly suggests that some corporate climate progress reflected accounting choices rather than actual reductions in grid emissions.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In response, some operators and researchers have proposed 24/7 carbon-free energy matching.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Under this approach, every hour of a facility's electricity use must be matched with carbon-free generation on the same regional grid.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The authors found that annual or volumetric matching did little to cut grid emissions under current U.S. policy.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Hourly 24/7 matching cut more, but it cost about $13 to $30 more per megawatt-hour.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] The tension between data center expansion and corporate climate goals has also become apparent in the operators' own disclosures of information.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google reported its greenhouse gas emissions had risen by about 48% since 2019, attributing the increase in large part to data center electricity use associated with AI workloads.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Similarly, Microsoft reported in 2024 that its emissions had risen by about 29% since 2020, citing the construction and operation of new data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p01] Moreover, the IEA projected in 2025 that global data center carbon dioxide emissions could peak at around 320 million tonnes by 2030 before declining slightly through 2035, with the trajectory depending heavily on the carbon intensity of the electricity supplied to new facilities.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Data centers have significant impacts on local ecologies, politics, and utility infrastructure.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Political and economic incentives such as tax breaks, land deals, or government subsidies drive data center growth in areas where these incentives are available.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Data centers are frequently located in rural areas, where they may displace agriculture.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Growth in the data center industry has prompted several debates about environmental impacts, especially the massive energy and water demands.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] The supply chains, emissions, and e-waste also impose significant planetary impacts, raising questions of environmental injustice toward marginalized communities that frequently bear these burdens.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Multiple studies and experts have found that data centers do not bring high-paying jobs to local communities in proportion to the tax subsidies they receive.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] The rapid expansion of AI data centers has raised significant concerns over their water consumption, particularly in drought-prone regions.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] According to the IEA, a single 100-megawatt data center, using 2400 MWh of electricity per day, can use up to 2,000,000 litres (530,000 US gal) of water per day.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] The electricity use is equivalent to that of 60,000–120,000 households in the U.S., while water use is equivalent about 6,500 households.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Water usage can be divided into three categories: on-site (direct usage from data centers), off-site (indirect usage from electricity), and supply-chain (water usage from manufacturing processes).
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] On-site water use refers to the direct water consumed by the data center for the cooling of its equipment.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Water is used specifically for space humidification (adding moisture to the air), evaporative cooling systems (cooling air before entering server rooms), and cooling towers (removing heat from the facility).
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Off-site water use is the indirect water usage from the electricity generated in data centers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] It is estimated that 56% of U.S. data centers' electricity comes from fossil fuels in thermal power stations, which use water to generate power via steam.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Lastly, data centers consume water through the process of AI chip and server manufacturing.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] These chips, specifically, consume a vast amount of ultrapure water for fabrication and cooling of semiconductor plants.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] While this scope of water usage is not as significant as on-site and off-site water usage, it is still a contributing factor.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Globally, since 2022, more than two-thirds of new data centers have been built in water-stressed areas, including Texas, Arizona, Saudi Arabia, and India, where freshwater scarcity is already a critical issue.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] The global water footprint of data centers is estimated at 560 billion litres (150×10^9 US gal) annually, a figure projected to double by 2030 due to increasing AI demand.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] In regions like Aragon, Spain, Amazon's planned data centers are licensed to withdraw 755,720 cubic metres (612.67 acre⋅ft) of water per year, sparking conflicts with farmers who rely on the same dwindling supplies.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Similar tensions have arisen in Chile, the Netherlands, and Uruguay, where communities protest the diversion of water for tech infrastructure.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Tech companies, including Microsoft, Google, and Amazon, have pledged to become "water positive" by 2030, aiming to replenish more water than they consume.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] However, critics argue that such commitments often rely on water offsetting, which does not address acute local shortages.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] At least 59 additional data centers are planned for water-stressed U.S. regions by 2028, and AI's global water demand is projected to reach 6.6 billion cubic metres (1,700×10^9 US gal) by 2027.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Data centers generate significant electronic waste (e-waste) due to the frequent replacement of hardware such as servers, GPUs, CPUs, memory, and storage devices, often every 2–5 years to meet demands for digital transformation and AI.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Globally, e-waste totaled 62 million metric tons in 2022, with generative AI projected to contribute 1.2 to 5 million metric tons annually by 2030, including valuable metals like copper and gold, and hazardous substances such as lead and mercury.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] In the U.S., data centers contribute to an annual loss of $10 billion in discarded e-waste value, including $4 billion in precious metals.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Only 22% of global e-waste is formally collected and recycled, exacerbating environmental pollution and health risks in informal processing sites, often in developing countries where exported waste is handled.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] From a political ecology perspective, data center e-waste highlights power imbalances in resource management and environmental justice, as tech corporations benefit from tax incentives while externalizing costs to marginalized communities through toxic exports and landfill burdens.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where shared resources like metals are depleted without equitable governance.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Mitigation strategies include modular hardware designs, secure data erasure for reuse, and extended producer responsibility policies to reduce waste by up to 86% in optimized scenarios.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] According to one 2025 energy model, the U.S. could see energy prices increase 8% nationally by 2030.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Higher electricity prices are already occurring in some regions, particularly those with lots of data centers like Santa Clara, California, and parts of upstate New York.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Data centers have also generated concerns in Northern Virginia about whether residents will have to foot the bill for future power lines.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] It has also made it harder to develop housing in London.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] A Bank of America Institute report in July 2024 found that increased demand for electricity due in part to AI has been pushing electricity prices higher and is a significant contributor to electricity inflation.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] A Harvard Law School report in March 2025 found that because utilities are increasingly in competition to attract data center contracts from big tech companies, they are likely hiding subsidies to those trillion-dollar companies in power prices by raising costs for American consumers.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Data centers have increasingly been analyzed through the lens of political ecology, which explores the intersections of power, politics, and environmental change in technological infrastructure.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Scholars argue that these facilities reshape urban and rural landscapes by existing in marginalized or post-industrial areas, often repurposing abandoned sites while promising economic revitalization through job creation and tax revenues.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] For instance, hyperscale data centers in rural towns like Prineville, Oregon, or Luleå, Sweden, challenge traditional core-periphery dynamics but can exacerbate global inequalities in digital access and resource distribution.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] In the context of digital transformation, data centers enable the expansion of cloud computing, AI, and machine learning, but at significant ecological and social costs.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Critics from science and technology studies (STS) highlight how corporate sustainability pledges, such as carbon neutrality targets by companies like Microsoft and Google, often rely on offsets and renewable subsidies that privatize benefits while causing social and environmental harms.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where data centers' intensive use of public resources (like electricity grids and water supplies) represents an enclosure, with tech firms receiving tax breaks and priority access at the expense of local communities.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Jobs created by data centers tend to be temporary or few in number.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] A study found the productivity increases enabled by data centers are multiple times larger than gross external damages.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Social mobilizations against data centers help shape the discourse around growth of the industry, raise public awareness of issues data centers present, and may impact public policy.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Groups opposed to new data center projects have expressed concern that digital infrastructure exploits local resources 'to the benefit of actors and institutions residing elsewhere'.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] This may occur when data being processed in a facility belongs to actors in other countries, but local people bear the burdens of water and energy use.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] In the U.S., bipartisan community resistance to data center development has grown, with residents voicing concerns about water scarcity, rising utility bills, noise pollution, and urban sprawl.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Facilities in rural areas of the U.S. have been focal points for local resistance.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Data Center Watch reported that multiple projects collectively worth $64 billion had been stopped or delayed between May 2024 and March 2025.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] An additional $98 billion worth of projects were blocked or delayed between March and June 2025.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] A Gallup poll taken in March 2026 reported seven out of ten Americans oppose data center projects in their area.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Outside of the U.S., protests in the Netherlands led to a temporary national ban on new mega-centers in 2022.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] In Chile, protests by activists to protect water reserves led to Google withdrawing plans to build a data center.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] In the United Kingdom, "March Against the Machines" protests were held.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Residents have been concerned about air, water, and noise pollution, as well as property devaluation, traffic, and the risk of fires.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Other environmental concerns involving AI data centers include e-waste and the embodied energy of construction materials, such as concrete and cement.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] data center, they would orbit above the dawn / dusk transition of the planet.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Housing data centers in space has been proposed for low Earth orbit (LEO).
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] The theoretical advantages are that of space-based solar power, in addition to aiding in weather forecasting and weather prediction computation from weather satellites, and the ability to freely scale up.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] However, it is difficult to design cooling systems in space, as convection is not available and sunlight causes large temperature fluctuations.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] Other challenges include damage from cosmic rays and micrometeorites.
[src:digitalocean/data-center-p02] The design and shape of data centers could change rapidly in the not-too-distant future with the advent of new technologies, such as quantum computing, biocomputation, and synthetic DNA data storage, as examples.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] DigitalOcean also runs Hacktoberfest, a one-month-long celebration of open-source software held in October.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] Each year, it partners with different software companies, including GitHub, Twilio, Dev.to, Intel, Appwrite and Deep Source.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In 2003, brothers Ben and Moisey Uretsky, who founded ServerStack, a managed hosting business, wanted to create a new product that would combine web hosting and virtual server and target entrepreneurial software developers.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In 2012, the Uretskys met co-founder Mitch Wainer following Wainer's response to a Craigslist job listing.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] The company launched their beta product in January 2012.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In mid-2012, the founding team consisted of Ben Uretsky, Moisey Uretsky, Mitch Wainer, Jeff Carr, and Alec Hartman.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] DigitalOcean accepted the offer of TechStars 2012's startup accelerator in Boulder, Colorado, and the founders moved to Boulder to work on the product.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] At the end of the accelerator program in August 2012, the company had signed up 400 customers and launched around 10,000 cloud server instances.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] On January 16, 2018, new *droplet* (virtual machines) plans were introduced.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In May 2018, the company announced the launch of its Kubernetes-based container service.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In June 2018, Mark Templeton, former CEO of Citrix, replaced co-founder Ben Uretsky as the company's CEO.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In July 2019, Yancey Spruill, former CFO and COO of SendGrid (a fellow Techstars company), replaced Templeton as CEO.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] Bill Sorenson, former CFO of EnerNOC, was appointed as the company's new CFO.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] Spruill left DigitalOcean in February 2024.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In September 2021, DigitalOcean announced plans to acquire Nimbella, a serverless startup.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In March 2022, the company acquired CSS-Tricks, a learning website for front-end developers.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In May 2022, the company released DigitalOcean Functions.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] Based on technology acquired from Nimbella and the open source Apache OpenWhisk project, DigitalOcean Functions is a serverless platform that allows developers to build and run applications without having to manage servers.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In August 2022, DigitalOcean acquired Cloudways, a Pakistani cloud hosting service provider, for $350 million in an all-cash deal.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In March 2025, Flexential announced a partnership with DigitalOcean to expand its GPU infrastructure.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] The partnership involves a phased deployment of high-density GPU servers at Flexential's Atlanta-Douglasville data center, aimed at supporting AI and machine learning workloads.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] This expansion is expected to provide additional GPU Droplets powered by NVIDIA H200 and AMD Instinct GPUs.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] On January 15, 2013, DigitalOcean became one of the first cloud-hosting companies to offer SSD-based virtual machines.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] Following a TechCrunch review, which was syndicated by Hacker News, DigitalOcean saw a rapid increase in customers.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In December 2013, DigitalOcean opened its first European data center, located in Amsterdam.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] During 2014, the company continued its expansion, opening new data centers in Singapore and London.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] During 2015 DigitalOcean expanded further with a data center in Toronto, Canada. and Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] Later in 2016, they continued expansion to Bangalore, India.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] The company's seed funding was led by IA Ventures and raised US$3.2 million in July 2013.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] Its series A round of funding in March 2014, led by venture capitalist firm Andreessen Horowitz, raised US$37.2 million.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In December 2014, DigitalOcean raised US$50 million in debt financing from Fortress Investment Group in the form of a five-year term loan.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In July 2015, the company raised US$83 million in its series B round of funding led by Access Industries with participation from Andreessen Horowitz.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In April 2016, the company secured US$130 million in credit financing to build out new cloud services.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In May 2020, DigitalOcean raised an additional $50 million from Access Industries and Andreessen Horowitz.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] On March 24, 2021, DigitalOcean became a publicly traded company on the New York Stock Exchange, with their initial public offering price at $47 per share.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In March 2026, DigitalOcean upsized stock offering to $800 million to fund its AI and infrastructure growth.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] Digital Ocean was blocked throughout Iran as part of its attempt to cut off use of the Lantern internet censorship circumvention tool.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] According to Russian law, any host keeping its citizens' personal data needs to be located in Russian territory.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] This law led to a temporary block in April 2018 of Google, Amazon, Azure, and DigitalOcean, among others, in Russia by Roskomnadzor as a hosting provider for Telegram Messenger and VPS services.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In early 2017, DigitalOcean expanded their feature set by adding load balancers to their offering.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] Their platform is an alternative cloud offering and the company targets smaller developers, allowing them to spend as little as five dollars on their platform.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] DigitalOcean can be managed through a web interface or using doctl command line.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] DigitalOcean also offers block and object-based storage and since May 2018 Kubernetes-based container service.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] Reviewers have noted that DigitalOcean requires users to have some experience in sysadmin and DevOps.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In his review for ScienceBlogs, writer Greg Laden warned: "DigitalOcean is not for everybody.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] You need to be at least a little savvy with Linux ...
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In 2021, DigitalOcean launched a managed MongoDB database service.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] As of 2021, DigitalOcean is hosting publicly available community forums and tutorials on open source and system administration topics.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] As of August 2014, the service claimed to have over 1,000 vetted tutorials.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] In 2017, in partnership with Stripe, DigitalOcean sponsored the Libscore tool to freely provide the developer community with open access to analytics on web development tools.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] DigitalOcean Marketplace provides facilities to deploy various software bundles.
[src:digitalocean/digitalocean] Internally, it's run by DigitalOcean Kubernetes, OpenChannel for the catalog API and data warehouse and Cloudflare for CDN and load-balancing.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS-cloud providers supply resources on-demand from the large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks, VPNs).
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] To deploy their applications, users install operating-system images and the application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] Users patch and maintain the operating systems.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS services are typically billed as a utility: cost reflects the amount of resources allocated or consumed.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] Typically, IaaS involves the use of a cloud orchestration technology such as OpenStack, Apache CloudStack, or OpenNebula.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] It manages the creation of a virtual machine (VM) and decides on the hypervisor (i.e. physical host) in order to start it.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] A hypervisor runs virtual machines (VMs) as guests.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] Pools of hypervisors in the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to demand by customers.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] Hypervisors include Xen, Oracle VirtualBox, Oracle VM, KVM, VMware ESX/ESXi, or Microsoft Hyper-V.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] It also enables VM migration between hosts, allocates storage volumes, and attaches them to VMs that track usage information for billing.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] An alternative to hypervisors is Linux containers, which run in isolated partitions of a Linux kernel that runs directly on the physical hardware.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] Containers are isolated, secured and managed using Linux cgroups and namespaces.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] Containerisation offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] The global IaaS market is projected to reach a value of $411.9 billion by 2030, expanding at a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 22.6% from 2023 to 2030.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] This growth is primarily driven by the adoption of cloud-based infrastructure within the Banking, Financial Services, and Insurance (BFSI) sector, which employs these technologies to enhance scalability and reduce operational costs.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to use public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:digitalocean/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS is in use within the UK Government but the technology community within government recommends consideration of Platform as a Service (PaaS) in cases where a department may not have IaaS skills and management capacity.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] A **solid-state drive** (**SSD**) is a type of solid-state storage device that uses integrated circuits to store data persistently.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] It is sometimes called **semiconductor storage device**, **solid-state device**, or **solid-state disk**.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Etymologically, "solid-state drive" partly refers to existing data storage devices like tape drives and hard disk drives, which all used a mechanically driven storage medium.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SSDs rely on non-volatile memory, typically NAND flash, to store data in memory cells.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The performance and endurance of SSDs vary depending on the number of bits stored per cell, ranging from high-performing single-level cells (SLC) to more affordable but slower quad-level cells (QLC).
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In addition to flash-based SSDs, other technologies such as 3D XPoint offer faster speeds and higher endurance through different data storage mechanisms.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Unlike traditional hard disk drives (HDDs), SSDs have no moving parts, allowing them to deliver faster data access speeds, reduced latency, increased resistance to physical shock, lower power consumption, and silent operation.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Often interfaced to a system in the same way as HDDs, SSDs are used in a variety of devices, including personal computers, enterprise servers, and mobile devices.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] However, SSDs are generally more expensive on a per-gigabyte basis and have a finite number of write cycles, which can lead to data loss over time.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Despite these limitations, SSDs are increasingly replacing HDDs, especially in performance-critical applications and as primary storage in many consumer devices.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SSDs come in various form factors and interface types, including SATA, PCIe, and NVMe, each offering different levels of performance.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Hybrid storage solutions, such as solid-state hybrid drives (SSHDs), combine SSD and HDD technologies to offer improved performance at a lower cost than pure SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] An SSD stores data in semiconductor cells, with its properties varying according to the number of bits stored in each cell (between 1 and 4).
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Single-level cells (SLC) store one bit of data per cell and provide higher performance and endurance.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In contrast, multi-level cells (MLC), triple-level cells (TLC), and quad-level cells (QLC) store more data per cell but have lower performance and endurance.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SSDs using 3D XPoint technology, such as Intel's Optane, store data by changing electrical resistance instead of storing electrical charges in cells, which can provide faster speeds and longer data persistence compared to conventional flash memory.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SSDs based on NAND flash slowly leak charge when not powered, while heavily used consumer drives may start losing data typically after one to two years unpowered in storage.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SSDs have a limited lifetime number of writes, and also slow down as they reach their full storage capacity.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SSDs also have internal parallelism that allows them to manage multiple operations simultaneously, which enhances their performance.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Unlike HDDs and similar electromechanical magnetic storage, SSDs do not have moving mechanical parts, which provides advantages such as resistance to physical shock, quieter operation, and faster access times.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Their lower latency results in higher input/output rates (IOPS) than HDDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Some SSDs are combined with traditional hard drives in hybrid configurations, such as Intel's Hystor and Apple's Fusion Drive.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] These drives use both flash memory and spinning magnetic disks in order to improve the performance of frequently accessed data.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SATA and SAS) and standard HDD form factors allow such SSDs to be used as drop-in replacements for HDDs in computers and other devices.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Newer form factors such as mSATA, M.2, U.2, NF1/M.3/NGFF, XFM Express (*Crossover Flash Memory*, form factor XT2) and EDSFF and higher speed interfaces such as NVM Express (NVMe) over PCI Express (PCIe) can further increase performance over HDD performance.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Traditional HDD benchmarks tend to focus on the performance characteristics such as rotational latency and seek time.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] As SSDs do not need to spin or seek to locate data, they are vastly superior to HDDs in such tests.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] However, SSDs have challenges with mixed reads and writes, and their performance may degrade over time.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Therefore, SSD testing typically looks at when the full drive is first used, as the new and empty drive may have much better write performance than it would show after only weeks of use.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The reliability of both HDDs and SSDs varies greatly among models.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Some field failure rates indicate that SSDs are significantly more reliable than HDDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] However, SSDs are sensitive to sudden power interruption, sometimes resulting in aborted writes or even cases of the complete loss of the drive.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Most of the advantages of solid-state drives over traditional hard drives are due to their ability to access data completely electronically instead of electromechanically, resulting in superior transfer speeds and mechanical ruggedness.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] On the other hand, hard disk drives offer significantly higher capacity for their price.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In traditional HDDs, a rewritten file will generally occupy the same location on the disk surface as the original file, whereas in SSDs the new copy will often be written to different NAND cells for the purpose of wear leveling.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The wear-leveling algorithms are complex and difficult to test exhaustively.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] As a result, one major cause of data loss in SSDs is firmware bugs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] While both memory cards and most SSDs use flash memory, they have very different characteristics, including power consumption, performance, size, and reliability.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Originally, solid state drives were shaped and mounted in the computer like hard drives.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In contrast, memory cards (such as Secure Digital (SD), CompactFlash (CF), and many others) were originally designed for digital cameras and later found their way into cell phones, gaming devices, GPS units, etc.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Most memory cards are physically smaller than SSDs, and designed to be inserted and removed repeatedly.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SSDs have different failure modes from traditional magnetic hard drives.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Because solid-state drives contain no moving parts, they are generally not subject to mechanical failures.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] However, other types of failures can occur.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For example, incomplete or failed writes due to sudden power loss may be more problematic than with HDDs, and the failure of a single chip may result in the loss of all data stored on it.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Nonetheless, studies indicate that SSDs are generally reliable, often exceeding their manufacturer-stated lifespan and have lower failure rates than HDDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] However, studies also note that SSDs experience higher rates of uncorrectable errors, which can lead to data loss, compared to HDDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The basic parameter for determining the lifespan of Flash-NAND systems is the number of programming-erase (P/E) cycles.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The TBW parameter is the product of the P/E cycle resource and the SSD capacity.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For an SSD with a capacity of 1 TB and TBW = 600 TB, the number of P/E cycles is 600.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Recovering data from SSDs presents challenges due to the non-linear and complex nature of data storage in solid-state drives.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The internal operations of SSDs vary by manufacturer, with commands (e.g.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] TRIM and the ATA Secure Erase) and programs (e.g. hdparm) being able to erase and modify the bits of a deleted file.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In a distributed computing environment, SSDs can be used as a distributed cache layer that temporarily absorbs the large volume of user requests to slower HDD-based backend storage systems.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] This layer provides much higher bandwidth and lower latency than the storage system would, and can be managed in a number of forms, such as a distributed key-value database and a distributed file system.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] On supercomputers, this layer is typically referred to as burst buffer.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Flash-based solid-state drives can be used to create network appliances from general-purpose personal computer hardware.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] A write protected flash drive containing the operating system and application software can substitute for larger, less reliable disk drives or CD-ROMs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Appliances built this way can provide an inexpensive alternative to expensive router and firewall hardware.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SSDs based on an SD card with a live SD operating system are easily write-locked.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Combined with a cloud computing environment or other writable medium, an OS booted from a write-locked SD card is reliable, persistent and impervious to permanent corruption.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In 2011, Intel introduced a caching mechanism for their Z68 chipset (and mobile derivatives) called Smart Response Technology, which allows a SATA SSD to be used as a cache (configurable as write-through or write-back) for a conventional, magnetic hard disk drive.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] A similar technology is available on HighPoint's RocketHybrid PCIe card.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Solid-state hybrid drives (SSHDs) are based on the same principle, but integrate some amount of flash memory on board of a conventional drive instead of using a separate SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The flash layer in these drives can be accessed independently from the magnetic storage by the host using ATA-8 commands, allowing the operating system to manage it.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For example, Microsoft's ReadyDrive technology explicitly stores portions of the hibernation file in the cache of these drives when the system hibernates, making the subsequent resume faster.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Dual-drive hybrid systems are combining the usage of separate SSD and HDD devices installed in the same computer, with overall performance optimization managed by the computer user, or by the computer's operating system software.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Examples of this type of system are bcache and dm-cache on Linux, and Apple's Fusion Drive.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The primary components of an SSD are the controller and the memory used to store data.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Traditionally, early SSDs used volatile DRAM for storage, but since 2009, most SSDs utilize non-volatile NAND flash memory, which retains data even when powered off.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Flash memory SSDs store data in metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) integrated circuit chips, using non-volatile floating-gate memory cells.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Every SSD includes a controller, which manages the data flow between the NAND memory and the host computer.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The controller is an embedded processor that runs firmware to optimize performance, managing data, and ensuring data integrity.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The overall performance of an SSD can scale with the number of parallel NAND chips and the efficiency of the controller.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For example, controllers that enable parallel processing of NAND flash chips can improve bandwidth and reduce latency.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The number of flash memory channel increases, the delay of raw flash memory (such as ONFI based NAND flash) decreases, and the bandwidth of raw flash memory increases.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Micron and Intel pioneered faster SSDs by implementing techniques such as data striping and interleaving to enhance read/write speeds.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] More recently, SandForce introduced controllers that incorporate data compression to reduce the amount of data written to the flash memory, potentially increasing both performance and endurance.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Wear leveling is a technique used in SSDs to ensure that write and erase operations are distributed evenly across all blocks of the flash memory.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Without this, specific blocks could wear out prematurely due to repeated use, reducing the overall lifespan of the SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The process moves data that is infrequently changed (cold data) from heavily used blocks, so that data that changes more frequently (hot data) can be written to those blocks.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] This helps distribute wear more evenly across the entire SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] However, this process introduces additional writes, known as write amplification, which must be managed to balance performance and durability.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Most SSDs use non-volatile NAND flash memory for data storage, primarily due to its cost-effectiveness and ability to retain data without a constant power supply.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] NAND flash-based SSDs store data in semiconductor cells, with the specific architecture influencing performance, endurance, and cost.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Over time, SSD controllers have improved the efficiency of NAND flash, incorporating techniques such as interleaved memory, advanced error correction, and wear leveling to optimize performance and extend the lifespan of the drive.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Lower-end SSDs often use QLC or TLC memory, while higher-end drives for enterprise or performance-critical applications may use MLC or SLC.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In addition to the flat (planar) NAND structure, many SSDs now use 3D NAND (or V-NAND), where memory cells are stacked vertically, increasing storage density while improving performance and reducing costs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Some SSDs use volatile DRAM instead of NAND flash, offering very high-speed data access but requiring a constant power supply to retain data.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] DRAM-based SSDs are typically used in specialized applications where performance is prioritized over cost or non-volatility.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Many SSDs, such as NVDIMM devices, are equipped with backup power sources such as internal batteries or external AC/DC adapters.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] These power sources ensure data is transferred to a backup system (usually NAND flash or another storage medium) in the event of power loss, preventing data corruption or loss.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Similarly, ULLtraDIMM devices use components designed for DIMM modules, but only use flash memory, similar to a DRAM SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] DRAM-based SSDs are often used for tasks where data must be accessed at high speeds with low latency, such as in high-performance computing or certain server environments.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] 3D XPoint is a type of non-volatile memory technology developed by Intel and Micron, announced in 2015.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] It operates by changing the electrical resistance of materials in its cells, offering much faster access times than NAND flash.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] 3D XPoint-based SSDs, such as Intel's Optane drives, provide lower latency and higher endurance than NAND-based drives, although they are more expensive per gigabyte.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Drives known as hybrid drives or solid-state hybrid drives (SSHDs) use a hybrid of spinning disks and flash memory.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Some SSDs use magnetoresistive random-access memory (MRAM) for storing data.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Many flash-based SSDs include a small amount of volatile DRAM as a cache, similar to the buffers in hard disk drives.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] This cache can temporarily hold data while it is being written to the flash memory, and it also stores metadata such as the mapping of logical blocks to physical locations on the SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] This cache may also temporarily hold data while it being recently read from the flash memory.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Some SSD controllers, like those from SandForce, achieve high performance without using an external DRAM cache.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] These designs rely on other mechanisms, such as on-chip SRAM, to manage data and minimize power consumption.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Additionally, some SSDs use an SLC buffer mechanism to temporarily store data in single-level cell (SLC) mode, even on multi-level cell (MLC) or triple-level cell (TLC) SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] This improves write performance by allowing data to be written to faster SLC storage before being moved to slower, higher-capacity MLC or TLC storage.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] On NVMe SSDs, Host Memory Buffer (HMB) technology allows the SSD to use a portion of the system's DRAM instead of relying on a built-in DRAM cache, reducing costs while maintaining a high level of performance.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In certain high-end consumer and enterprise SSDs, larger amounts of DRAM are included to cache both file table mappings and written data, reducing write amplification and enhances overall performance.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Higher-performing SSDs may include capacitors, supercapacitors or batteries, which helps preserve data integrity in the event of an unexpected power loss.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The capacitor or battery provides enough power to allow the data in the cache to be written to the non-volatile memory, ensuring no data is lost.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In some SSDs that use multi-level cell (MLC) flash memory, a potential issue known as "lower page corruption" can occur if power is lost while programming an upper page.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] This can result in previously written data becoming corrupted.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] To address this, some high-end SSDs incorporate supercapacitors to ensure all data can be safely written during a sudden power loss.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Some consumer SSDs have built-in capacitors to save critical data such as the Flash Translation Layer (FTL) mapping table.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Examples include the Crucial M500 and Intel 320 series.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Enterprise-class SSDs, such as the Intel DC S3700 series, often come with more robust power-loss protection mechanisms like supercapacitors or batteries.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The host interface of an SSD refers to the physical connector and the signaling methods used to communicate between the SSD and the host system.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] This interface is managed by the SSD's controller and is often similar to those found in traditional hard disk drives (HDDs).
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SSDs may support various logical interfaces, which define the command sets used by operating systems to communicate with the SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The size and shape of any device are largely driven by the size and shape of the components used to make that device.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Traditional HDDs and optical drives are designed around the rotating platter(s) or optical disc along with the spindle motor inside.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Since an SSD is made up of various interconnected integrated circuits (ICs) and an interface connector, its shape is no longer limited to the shape of rotating media drives.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The lack of moving parts and light weight meant that an SSD can have no shell and simply appear in the shape of a plug-in board.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] On the other end of the size spectrum, some solid-state storage solutions come in a larger chassis that may even be a rack-mount form factor with numerous SSDs inside.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] They would all connect to a common bus inside the chassis and connect outside the box with a single connector.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For general computer use, the 2.5-inch form factor (typically found in laptops and used for most SATA SSDs) was the most popular in the 2010s, in three thicknesses (7.0mm, 9.5mm, 14.8 or 15.0mm; with 12.0mm also available for some models).
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For desktop computers with 3.5-inch hard disk drive slots, a simple adapter plate can be used to make such a drive fit.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Other types of form factors are more common in enterprise applications.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] An SSD can also be completely integrated in the other circuitry of the device, as in the Apple MacBook Air (starting with the fall 2010 model).
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] As of 2014, mSATA and M.2 form factors also gained popularity, primarily in laptops.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The benefit of using a current HDD form factor would be to take advantage of the extensive infrastructure already in place to mount and connect the drives to the host system.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] These traditional form factors are known by the size of the rotating media (i.e., 5.25-inch, 3.5-inch, 2.5-inch or 1.8-inch) and not the dimensions of the drive casing.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] A *disk-on-a-module* (*DOM*) is a flash drive with either 40/44-pin Parallel ATA (PATA) or SATA interface, intended to be plugged directly into the motherboard and used as a computer hard disk drive (HDD).
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] DOM devices emulate a traditional hard disk drive, resulting in no need for special drivers or other specific operating system support.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] DOMs are usually used in embedded systems, which are often deployed in harsh environments where mechanical HDDs would simply fail, or in thin clients because of small size, low power consumption, and silent operation.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The most traditional emulates the standard interface, with the 7-pin SATA data connector placed beside the 15-pin SATA power connector.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] An example is the "half-slim SATA" MO-297 size standard.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] To save board space, smaller SATA DOMs were made that only use the SATA data connector.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Supermicro, relied on a separate Berg connector to deliver power.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] A second type of 2012, made by Innodisk, repurposes the 7th pin of the connector from GND to VCC (+5V).
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] A third type called "pin 8 power" replaces the two plastic structural elements on the sides with two metal contacts for GND and VCC.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] These new types of SATADOMs are now so popular that the older 7+15-pin type is virtually not considered to be "SATADOMs" any more, especially as few motherboards provide such an interface.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] There are also USB DOMs designed to be plugging into the USB 2.0 header pins on a motherboard.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] As of 2016, DOM storage capacities range from 4 MB to 128 GB with different variations in physical layouts, including vertical or horizontal orientation.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For applications where space is at a premium, like for ultrabooks or tablet computers, a few compact form factors were standardized for flash-based SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] There is the mSATA form factor, which uses the PCI Express Mini Card physical layout.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] It remains electrically compatible with the PCI Express Mini Card interface specification while requiring an additional connection to the SATA host controller through the same connector.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] A higher-performance SSD may use the Mini-PCIe to access the PCIe bus directly.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] M.2 form factor, formerly known as the Next Generation Form Factor (NGFF), is a natural transition from the mSATA and physical layout it used, to a more usable and more advanced form factor.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] While mSATA took advantage of an existing form factor and connector, M.2 has been designed to maximize usage of the card space, while minimizing the footprint.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The M.2 standard allows both SATA and PCI Express SSDs to be fitted onto M.2 modules.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Before M.2 was standardized, one of the main ways to access the PCIe bus for faster-than-SATA/SAS speed on a server was through the PCIe slot.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] A common shape is called HHHL (Half Height Half Length), or AIC (Add in Card) SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Some primitive PCIe SSDs do not access the PCIe bus directly, but simply had a PCIe-to-SATA/SAS bridge device and a number of SATA or SAS flash controllers attached.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] This was considered acceptable in 2010, when true PCIe SSDs were still new.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] This shape remains in use for some high performance, high capacity drives.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The PCIe slot offers 16 lanes of data and 75 watts of power, still much larger than what a M.2 slot can provide.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] It also provides space for a large heat sink.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] There are also adapter boards that converts other form factors, especially M.2 drives with PCIe interface, into regular add-in cards.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In the early 2000s, a few companies introduced SSDs in Ball Grid Array (BGA) form factors, such as M-Systems' (now SanDisk) DiskOnChip and Silicon Storage Technology's NANDrive (now produced by Greenliant Systems), and Memoright's M1000 for use in embedded systems.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The main benefits of BGA SSDs are their low power consumption, small chip package size to fit into compact subsystems, and that they can be soldered directly onto a system motherboard to reduce adverse effects from vibration and shock.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Such embedded drives now often adhere to the eMMC and eUFS standards.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Many of the DRAM-based solutions in 2014 use a box that is often designed to fit in a rack-mount system.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The number of DRAM components required to get sufficient capacity to store the data along with the backup power supplies requires a larger space than traditional HDD form factors.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The flexibility of the SSD also allows for many unusual form factors, some of which had been important in its early adoption in PCs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For example, the SATADIMM from Viking Technology uses an empty DDR3 DIMM slot on the motherboard to provide power to the SSD with a separate SATA connector to provide the data connection back to the computer.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The result is an easy-to-install SSD with a capacity equal to drives that typically take a full 2.5-inch drive bay.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The first devices resembling solid-state drives (SSDs) used semiconductor technology, with an early example being the 1978 StorageTek STC 4305.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] This device was a plug-compatible replacement for the IBM 2305 hard drive, initially using charge-coupled devices for storage and later switching to dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The STC 4305 was significantly faster than its mechanical counterparts and cost around $400,000 for a 45 MB capacity.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Though early SSD-like devices existed, they were not widely used due to their high cost and small storage capacity.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In the late 1980s, companies like Zitel began selling DRAM-based SSD products under the name "RAMDisk." These devices were primarily used in specialized systems like those made by UNIVAC and Perkin-Elmer.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Top and bottom sides of a 100GB Intel DC S3700 SATA SSD and a 120GB Intel 535 mSATA SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Flash memory, a key component in modern SSDs, was invented in 1980 by Fujio Masuoka at Toshiba.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Flash-based SSDs were patented in 1989 by the founders of SanDisk, which released its first product in 1991: a 20 MB SSD for IBM laptops.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] While the storage capacity was limited and the price high (around $1,000), this marked the beginning of a transition to flash memory as an alternative to traditional hard drives.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In the 1990s, new manufacturers of flash memory drives emerged, including STEC, Inc., M-Systems, and BiTMICRO.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] As the technology advanced, SSDs saw dramatic improvements in capacity, speed, and affordability.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] By 2016, commercially available SSDs had more capacity than the largest available HDDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] By 2018, flash-based SSDs had reached capacities of up to 100 TB in enterprise products, with consumer SSDs offering up to 16 TB.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] These advancements were accompanied by significant increases in read and write speeds, with some high-end consumer models reaching speeds of up to 14.5 GB/s.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In 2021, NVMe 2.0 with Zoned Namespaces (ZNS) was announced.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] ZNS allows data to be mapped directly to its physical location in memory, providing direct access on an SSD without a flash translation layer.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In 2024, Samsung announced what it called the world's first SSD with a hybrid PCIe interface, the Samsung 990 EVO.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The hybrid interface runs in either the x4 PCIe 4.0 or x2 PCIe 5.0 modes, a first for an M.2 SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SSD prices have also fallen dramatically, with the cost per gigabyte decreasing from around $50,000 in 1991 to less than $0.05 by 2020.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Enterprise flash drives (EFDs) are designed for high-performance applications requiring fast input/output operations per second (IOPS), reliability, and energy efficiency.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] EFDs often have higher specifications than consumer SSDs, making them suitable for mission-critical applications.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The term was first used by EMC in 2008 to describe SSDs built for enterprise environments.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] One example of an EFD is the Intel DC S3700 series, launched in 2012.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] These drives were notable for their consistent performance, maintaining IOPS variation within a narrow range, which is crucial for enterprise environments.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Another significant product is the Toshiba PX02SS series, launched in 2016.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Designed for write-intensive applications like online transaction processing, these drives achieved impressive read and write speeds and high endurance ratings.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In 2017, Intel introduced SSDs based on 3D XPoint technology under the Optane brand.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Unlike NAND flash, 3D XPoint uses a different method to store data, offering higher IOPS performance, although sequential read and write speeds remain slower compared to traditional SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] As SSD technology continues to improve, they are increasingly used in ultra-mobile PCs and lightweight laptop systems.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The first flash-memory SSD based PC to become available was the Sony Vaio UX90, announced for pre-order on 27 June 2006 and began shipping in Japan on 3 July 2006 with a 16 GB flash memory hard drive.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Another of the first mainstream releases of SSD was the XO Laptop, built as part of the One Laptop Per Child project.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Mass production of these computers, built for children in developing countries, began in December 2007.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] By 2009, Dell, Toshiba, Asus, Apple, and Lenovo had begun producing laptops with SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] By 2010, Apple's MacBook Air line began using solid state drives as the default.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In 2011, Intel's Ultrabook became the first widely available consumer computers using SSDs aside from the MacBook Air.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] At present, SSD devices are widely used and distributed by a number of companies, with a small number of companies manufacturing the NAND flash devices within them.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] SSD shipments were approximately 11 million units in 2009, rising to 17.3 million units in 2011 for a total market value of US$5 billion.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Shipments continued to grow to 39 million units in 2012 and were projected to reach 83 million units in 2013, 201.4 million units in 2016, and 227 million units in 2017.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The global solid-state drive (SSD) market is projected to grow significantly between 2024 and 2030, driven by rising demand for data center expansion, cloud computing services, and consumer electronics upgrades.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In a 2024 report, Grand View Research estimated the SSD market at USD 19.1 billion in 2023 and projected it to reach USD 55.1 billion by 2030.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In a separate 2024 study, Mordor Intelligence valued the market at USD 63.45 billion for 2024, forecasting growth to USD 172.82 billion by 2030.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The same file systems used on hard disk drives can typically also be used on solid state drives.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] File systems that support SSDs generally also support the TRIM command, which helps the SSD to recycle discarded data.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The file system does not need to manage wear leveling or other flash memory characteristics, as they are handled internally by the SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] F2FS, JFFS2) help to reduce write amplification on SSDs, especially in situations where only very small amounts of data are changed, such as when updating file-system metadata.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] If an operating system does not support using TRIM on discrete swap partitions, it might be possible to use swap files inside an ordinary file system instead.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For example, macOS does not support swap partitions; it only swaps to files within a file system, so it can use TRIM when, for example, swap files are deleted.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Since 2010, standard Linux drive utilities have taken care of appropriate partition alignment by default.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Kernel support for the TRIM operation was introduced in version 2.6.33 of the Linux kernel mainline, released on 24 February 2010.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The ext4, Btrfs, XFS, JFS, and F2FS file systems include support for the discard (TRIM or UNMAP) function.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Non-native file systems such as exFAT and NTFS-3G also support TRIM.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] To automatically make use of TRIM on file deletion, a file system must be mounted using the `discard` parameter.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Linux swap partitions are by default performing discard operations when the underlying drive supports TRIM, with the possibility to turn them off.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Support for queued TRIM, a SATA 3.1 feature that results in TRIM commands not disrupting the command queues, was introduced in Linux kernel 3.12, released on November 2, 2013.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] An alternative to the kernel-level TRIM operation is to use a user-space utility called fstrim that goes through all of the unused blocks in a filesystem and dispatches TRIM commands for those areas.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Thefstrimutility is usually run by cron or systemd as a scheduled task.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] A filesystem that supports TRIM remains required.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Whether formatting or resizing trims the unused space depends on the implementation.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For example, the mke2fs program for formatting ext2/3/4 defaults to issuing a TRIM command (if supported) to the entire block, but the resize2fs program for resizing ext2/3/4 does not TRIM the space left unused after shrinking.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] TRIM-after-resize is instead done by fdisk or sfdisk, programs that edit the partition table.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] In addition, bcache is designed to have an SSD act as a read/write cache for a slower drive such as an HDD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Versions since Mac OS X 10.6.8 (Snow Leopard) support TRIM but only when used with an Apple-purchased SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] TRIM is not automatically enabled for third-party drives, except for external removable SSDs, although it can be enabled by using third-party utilities such as *Trim Enabler*.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The status of TRIM can be checked in the System Information application or in the `system_profiler` command-line tool.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Versions since OS X 10.10.4 (Yosemite) include `sudo trimforce enable` as a Terminal command that enables TRIM on non-Apple SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] There is also a technique to enable TRIM in versions earlier than Mac OS X 10.6.8, although it remains uncertain whether TRIM is actually utilized properly in those cases.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Prior to Windows 7, Microsoft Windows did not take any specific measures to support solid state drives.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] From Windows 7, the standard NTFS file system provides support for the TRIM command.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] By default, Windows 7 and newer versions execute TRIM commands automatically if the device is detected to be a solid-state drive *and* the filesystem driver supports TRIM (NTFS or ReFS).
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] However, because TRIM irreversibly resets all freed space, it may be desirable to disable support where enabling data recovery is preferred over wear leveling.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Windows implements TRIM for more than just file-delete operations.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The TRIM operation is integrated with partition- and volume-level commands such as *format* and *delete*, with file-system commands relating to truncate and compression, and with the System Restore (also known as Volume Snapshot) feature.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The SuperFetch feature will also not materially improve performance and causes additional overhead in the system and SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Since Windows 8.1, the Windows Defrag routine would instead "retrim" (TRIM) partitions detected as SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Windows Vista generally expects hard disk drives rather than SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Windows Vista includes ReadyBoost to exploit characteristics of USB-connected flash devices, but for SSDs it only improves the default partition alignment to prevent read-modify-write operations that reduce the speed of SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Most SSDs are typically split into 4 KiB sectors, while earlier systems may be based on 512 byte sectors with their default partition setups unaligned to the 4 KiB boundaries.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Windows Vista does not send the TRIM command to solid-state drives, but some third-party utilities such as SSD Doctor will periodically scan the drive and TRIM the appropriate entries.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Windows 7 and later versions have native support for SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The operating system detects the presence of an SSD and optimizes operation accordingly.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For SSD devices, Windows 7 disables ReadyBoost and automatic defragmentation.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Despite the initial statement by Steven Sinofsky before the release of Windows 7, however, defragmentation is not disabled, even though its behavior on SSDs differs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] One reason is the low performance of Volume Shadow Copy Service on fragmented SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The second reason is to avoid reaching the practical maximum number of file fragments that a volume can handle.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Windows 7 also includes support for the TRIM command to reduce garbage collection for data that the operating system has already determined is no longer valid.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Windows 8.1 and later Windows systems also support automatic TRIM for PCI Express SSDs based on NVMe.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] For Windows 7, the KB2990941 update is required for this functionality and needs to be integrated into Windows Setup using DISM if Windows 7 has to be installed on the NVMe SSD.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Windows 8/8.1 also supports the SCSI unmap command, an analog of SATA TRIM, for USB-attached SSDs or SATA-to-USB enclosures.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] It is also supported over USB Attached SCSI Protocol (UASP).
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] While Windows 7 supported automatic TRIM for internal SATA SSDs, Windows 8.1 and above support manual TRIM as well as automatic TRIM for SATA, NVMe and USB-attached SSDs.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Manual TRIM is accessed through the expanded Windows Defrag utility.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] Solaris as of version 10 Update 6 (released in October 2008), and recent versions of OpenSolaris, Solaris Express Community Edition, Illumos, Linux with ZFS on Linux, and FreeBSD all can use SSDs as a performance booster for ZFS.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] A low-latency SSD can be used for the ZFS Intent Log (ZIL), where it is named the SLOG.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] An SSD may also be used for the level 2 Adaptive Replacement Cache (L2ARC), which is used to cache data for reading.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] ZFS for FreeBSD introduced support for TRIM on September 23, 2012.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The Unix File System also supports the TRIM command.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The following are noted standardization organizations and bodies that work to create standards for solid-state drives (and other computer storage devices).
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] The table below also includes organizations which promote the use of solid-state drives.
[src:digitalocean/solid-state-drive] This is not necessarily an exhaustive list.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] A **virtual private server** (**VPS**) or **virtual dedicated server** (**VDS**) is a virtual machine sold as a service by an Internet hosting company.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] A virtual private server runs its own copy of an operating system (OS), and customers may have superuser-level access to that operating system instance, so they can install almost any software that runs on that OS.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] For many purposes, it is functionally equivalent to a dedicated physical server and, being software-defined, can be created and configured more easily.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] A virtual server costs less than an equivalent physical server.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] However, as virtual servers share the underlying physical hardware with other VPS, performance may be lower depending on the workload of any other executing virtual machines.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] The force driving server virtualization is similar to that which led to the development of time-sharing and multiprogramming in the past.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] Partitioning a single server to appear as multiple servers has been increasingly common on microcomputers since the release of VMware ESX Server in 2001.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] VMware later replaced ESX Server with VMware ESXi, a more lightweight hypervisor architecture that eliminated the Linux-based Console Operating System (COS) used in the original ESX.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] The physical server typically runs a hypervisor which is tasked with creating, releasing, and managing the resources of "guest" operating systems, or virtual machines.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] These guest operating systems are allocated a share of resources of the physical server, typically in a manner in which the guest is not aware of any other physical resources except for those allocated to it by the hypervisor.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] There are several approaches to virtualization.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] In hardware virtualization, a hypervisor such as the Kernel-based Virtual Machine allows each virtual machine (VM) to run its own independent kernel, providing greater isolation from the host system.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] By contrast, container-based virtualization—for example OpenVZ—shares the host kernel among multiple containers.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] This can improve resource efficiency, but usually offers less isolation and fewer customization options for each instance.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] Many companies offer virtual private server hosting or virtual dedicated server hosting as an extension for web hosting services.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] There are several challenges to consider when licensing proprietary software in multi-tenant virtual environments.
[src:digitalocean/virtual-private-server] With *unmanaged* or *self-managed* hosting, the customer is left to administer their own server instance.
